{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"280d0e01-d33b-4189-9a28-0aa17628cee9","content":"Here's a step-by-step diagnostic and fix plan for your situation:\n\n---\n\n## Phase 1 — Diagnose\n\nRun these in an **elevated** (admin) terminal:\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Which SDKs are installed?\ndotnet --list-sdks\n\n# 2. Which workloads are currently installed and their versions?\ndotnet workload list\n\n# 3. What does the build actually say? (from your project folder)\ndotnet build -v diag 2>&1 | Select-String -Pattern \"workload|android|error\"\n```\n\nWrite down:\n- The **new SDK version** (e.g. `9.0.200`)\n- Which workloads appear (e.g. `maui-windows`, `android`)\n- The exact error codes (commonly `NETSDK1147`, `NETSDK1178`, or `XA0000`-series)\n\n---\n\n## Phase 2 — Align workloads to the new SDK\n\n`dotnet workload update` **is safe** — it updates workload manifests + packs to match your current SDK band. Run it in an admin terminal:\n\n```powershell\n# 4. Update workload manifests & packs\ndotnet workload update\n\n# 5. If the above doesn't list maui, install it explicitly\ndotnet workload install maui\n```\n\nIf you get source errors, add the official feed:\n\n```powershell\ndotnet workload update --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n---\n\n## Phase 3 — Fix Android SDK\n\nWorkload update pulls the .NET Android bindings, but the **Android SDK platform tools / build-tools** may still be stale or missing.\n\n```powershell\n# 6. Check what Android SDK path .NET is using\ndotnet build -t:ResolveAndroidTooling -v diag 2>&1 | Select-String \"AndroidSdkPath\"\n\n# 7. Verify / update via the SDK manager (typical path shown)\n& \"$env:LOCALAPPDATA\\Android\\Sdk\\cmdline-tools\\latest\\bin\\sdkmanager.bat\" --list\n& \"$env:LOCALAPPDATA\\Android\\Sdk\\cmdline-tools\\latest\\bin\\sdkmanager.bat\" --update\n\n# 8. Accept all licenses\n& \"$env:LOCALAPPDATA\\Android\\Sdk\\cmdline-tools\\latest\\bin\\sdkmanager.bat\" --licenses\n```\n\nIf your project targets a specific API level (e.g. 34), make sure it's installed:\n\n```powershell\n& \"$env:LOCALAPPDATA\\Android\\Sdk\\cmdline-tools\\latest\\bin\\sdkmanager.bat\" `\n    \"platforms;android-34\" \"build-tools;34.0.0\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## Phase 4 — Verify\n\n```powershell\n# 9.  Confirm workloads are consistent\ndotnet workload list\n\n# 10. Clean & rebuild\ndotnet clean\ndotnet build\n```\n\n---\n\n### Quick-reference troubleshooting\n\n| Symptom | Fix |\n|---|---|\n| `NETSDK1147` – workload not installed | `dotnet workload install maui` |\n| `XA5300` – Android SDK not found | Set `<AndroidSdkDirectory>` in csproj or env var `ANDROID_HOME` |\n| `NETSDK1178` – version mismatch | `dotnet workload update` (resolves manifest drift) |\n| Java version error | Ensure **JDK 17** is on PATH (`java -version`) |\n\n**TL;DR** — `dotnet workload update` is non-destructive and is exactly the right first step. Follow it with an Android SDK manager `--update` and `--licenses` to cover the native toolchain side.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2fb3819c-f288-4003-ae50-6a8d60921809","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The working directory is empty. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI workloads and Android SDK issues. I'll provide a comprehensive diagnostic and fix plan based on my knowledge.","outputTokens":972,"requestId":"F407:12A859:1EACA94:228A7AA:69E81BAE"},"id":"a9356adc-0b9b-42fa-8840-ac73b3a7dd30","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:52:17.639Z","parentId":"80f9e8e9-cd50-4525-ac43-25e82999e3ec"}
